# Frontend Architecture and Styling Principles

Apply these rules strictly for frontend feature work.

## A) Separation of concerns

- UI (components/pages) must only render and handle user events.
- Forbidden inside UI: API calls, DTO types, validation logic, business logic, API-to-domain mapping.
- Business logic must be in feature/model or feature/hooks.
- API calls must live in `shared/api` (HTTP client) or `feature/api` (feature-specific requests and query hooks).

## B) Types and validation

- All domain types go into `.types.ts` files inside `feature/domain`.
- Define Zod schemas once for input and reuse everywhere.
- API DTO types must not be exposed in UI.

## C) Data fetching

- Use React Query (TanStack Query) hooks only in model/hooks layer.
- No React Query inside UI components directly.
- UI should consume custom feature hooks.

## D) Reusability and DRY

- If similar JSX appears multiple times, extract a reusable UI component.
- If logic repeats, extract a pure helper or custom hook.
- Do not duplicate query keys, constants, selectors, validation, or types.

## E) Testability

- Domain/business logic must be pure and testable independent of React.
- API ↔ domain mapping functions must be pure and testable.
- Even without tests now, keep structure test-friendly without hacks.

## F) UI complexity

- Keep components small and focused.
- Avoid nested JSX deeper than ~3 levels; extract subcomponents.
- Avoid inline complex types; prefer named types from `.types.ts`.

## G) Local state

- Do not store server state in local state unless necessary.
- Compute derived state instead of storing it.

## Complexity Rules

- No file over ~200 lines.
- No nested JSX deeper than 3 levels.
- No inline style objects in pages.
- Extract repeated layout blocks.

## Forbidden Patterns

- Direct `fetch`/`axios` calls in UI.
- Inline Zod schemas in components.
- DTO types in pages or components.
- Duplicated types/constants.
- Nested ternaries in JSX.
